On the other hand, the conversion offer of the Transylvania Bank was accepted by 83% of clients with loans in French due to the second successive reductions: the balance was reduced with the value of the risk and administration commissions paid by the client, then an additional 22.5% reduction was applied to the balance in the lei.
Both offers reduce the rates of their customers, compared to the equivalent monthly platform in lei before conversion.
Thus, Banca Transilvania reduces the rate by 42.5% and Bancpost by 33% in the first three years and, theoretically, by 18% in the next few years.
Benefits
The main advantage of the cover in the lei of credits in CHF is that the currency risk is eliminated, the consumer being protected by future increases of the franc, and the repayment of the credit will be made in the currency in which he cashs his salary.
Another major advantage of both conversion offers is that the property is not re-assessed, additional guarantees are no longer required, and another proof of revenue is required.
Basically, there will be no new financial and legal analysis of the credit and no additional costs as in the case of a refinancing.
Also, both banks offer discount at the monthly rate, compared to the customer tray before conversion, equivalent in lei.
Risks
The problem is that the rate in the first years is formed more of the interest, and the client pays very little of the principal.
The Bancpost offer with very small interest in the first three years seems advantageous to customers.
It is not known how this interest will evolve after three years.
The margin offered to customers can be more than 3.25%, so in total, and the cost reduction is smaller.
