The map is meant to remind that Janet L. Yellen, President Fed, and his colleagues must put the nation's economic interests above everything else.
The Central Bank has received a dual task from the Congress: to maximise the employment rate in the US and to maintain price stability.
But since the big economic crisis, Fed leaders have confirmed that there is a third unwritten task: financial stability.
And this third task could be factor X in a decision too difficult to anticipate, which will be announced on Tuesday, and which will determine whether the US economy is prepared to be stripped of the unprecedented stimulus offered by the close-to-zero short-term interest rate in effect since the end of 2008.
Even if most data indicate a strong growing economy, recent turmoil in global financial markets could scare Fed officials already cautious about adding volatility by increasing the reference rate to federal funds - even with only a quarter of a percentage point.
"Obviously, the labour market and inflation will be the first and main aspects they will pursue," said Lindsey M. Piegza, chief economist at the brokerage firm Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
